- Hi, Max! Hi.
- Hi!

00:49.520 --> 00:54.321
You have one little corner
of baby smell left right there.

00:55.640 --> 00:57.051
- Hi, how are you?
- I need a baby!

00:57.160 --> 00:58.764
You need a baby?

00:58.840 --> 01:01.411
You're such an impatient little fussbudget.

01:01.480 --> 01:03.881
I just don't see why I should wait.

01:04.000 --> 01:05.364
For a father, perhaps?

01:05.800 --> 01:07.086
Let's face it.

01:07.160 --> 01:11.245
I've never been in a serious relationship
that's lasted longer than six months.

01:11.320 --> 01:12.526
We were together for two years.

01:12.600 --> 01:13.601
Thanks.

01:13.680 --> 01:16.968
In college. And we made each other
miserable the rest of the time.

01:17.040 --> 01:18.405
- Yeah.
- Here you go.

01:18.480 --> 01:22.087
I admit it, we were miserable,

01:22.160 --> 01:24.527
- but we were also happy.
- Yeah.

01:24.600 --> 01:25.726
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

01:25.840 --> 01:30.004
Well, just so you know,
I have some sperm in a facility uptown,

01:30.080 --> 01:31.605
if you're in a pinch.

01:31.680 --> 01:32.920
What? Why?

01:33.000 --> 01:35.128
I thought Felicia
didn't want any more kids.

01:35.240 --> 01:39.290
Felicia does not want any more kids.
I froze it in case I met someone nice.

01:40.000 --> 01:41.126
No, you didn't.

01:42.600 --> 01:43.886
I didn't.

01:44.200 --> 01:47.602
But I might.
You know, save it like mad money style.

01:49.720 --> 01:54.169
So do you remember
Guy Childers from college?

01:54.600 --> 01:57.888
Wait, wasn't he the guy, he now...
What, he's a pickle salesman, right?

01:57.960 --> 02:00.327
No, he's a pickle entrepreneur.

02:00.400 --> 02:01.731
I'm just gonna touch these.

02:02.840 --> 02:07.482
And he agreed to make a donation,
so that I could inseminate myself.

02:08.360 --> 02:12.763
- But he has no sense of personal space.
- So what? He was a math major.

02:12.840 --> 02:16.640
And I'm not gonna marry him.
I'm just borrowing his genes.

02:16.720 --> 02:19.405
But not his personality, I hope.
Guy Childers?

02:19.480 --> 02:21.528
Well, everybody's got something
a little bit wrong with them.

02:21.600 --> 02:23.807
You think everybody's honest
who fills out those questionnaires

02:23.880 --> 02:25.564
at the sperm bank donation thing?

02:25.640 --> 02:28.166
I can't believe you've been cooking this up
and you didn't even tell me.

02:28.240 --> 02:30.811
- Because I knew that you'd yell at me.
- I'm not yelling at you...

02:30.920 --> 02:34.925
Isn't this something that women do
who are, like, 49 and desperate?

02:35.040 --> 02:36.849
I don't want it to be a last resort.

02:36.920 --> 02:40.402
I want it to be a choice
because I'm ready to be a mother,

02:40.480 --> 02:43.882
and I don't believe that I'll find someone
that I can stay in love with

02:43.960 --> 02:47.760
or who can stay in love with me
for longer than six months.

02:47.840 --> 02:50.605
I'm just facing the truth about myself.

02:52.760 --> 02:55.809
So when's the insemination?
Are we gonna have a party?

02:56.160 --> 02:57.730
In four months.

03:01.080 --> 03:03.128
Hey, does my breath smell?

03:04.520 --> 03:07.126
No. Does mine?

03:22.800 --> 03:25.041
I started production in my apartment
three years ago.

03:25.120 --> 03:27.088
Now, I have 12 employees.

03:27.720 --> 03:32.044
And I just got an order from Whole Foods.
So if that works out, we're taking off.

03:32.120 --> 03:34.691
But I'm still very hands-on.

03:35.200 --> 03:38.488
Every pickle has my stamp
of approval on it.

03:39.960 --> 03:41.724
Here, try this one.

03:45.040 --> 03:46.246
I love this.

03:46.320 --> 03:48.641
That's a Bavarian. It's classic.

03:48.960 --> 03:51.611
This is the best pickle I've ever had.

03:54.880 --> 03:58.885
- You skate?
- Yeah. Every Sunday.

03:59.800 --> 04:01.564
I grew up on the ice.

04:01.640 --> 04:04.689
- Right. You were on the ice hockey team.
- Yeah.

04:04.840 --> 04:07.844
I used to ice-skate a lot
when I was little.

04:09.080 --> 04:11.845
- So regarding our plan.
- Okay.

04:13.240 --> 04:14.446
Here

04:15.880 --> 04:17.689
is my bill of health.

04:19.160 --> 04:20.446
Read it.

04:21.680 --> 04:22.920
That's great.

04:23.800 --> 04:25.529
I have for you...

04:28.320 --> 04:30.243
You need to keep it warm when you...

04:30.400 --> 04:33.131
So just put it next to your body,
underneath your shirt,

04:33.240 --> 04:35.971
- and you can come right over.
- Okay.

04:39.600 --> 04:41.921
So when do you want to do this?

04:42.360 --> 04:43.885
March 23rd.

04:46.880 --> 04:50.202
- I just want to build up some more savings.
- Please. That's smart.

04:51.600 --> 04:54.331
I already have health insurance
and everything.

04:54.520 --> 04:57.524
So I guess the question is,

04:59.040 --> 05:01.930
how much involvement do you want to have?

05:03.000 --> 05:08.450
I was going to suggest none,
but I'm open to negotiation.

05:09.000 --> 05:11.970
None is so cool.

05:13.080 --> 05:14.081
Yeah.

05:15.400 --> 05:19.121
I mean, that kind of takes
the pressure off, right? Doesn't it?

05:19.280 --> 05:21.931
I can just relax and build my empire.

05:22.080 --> 05:23.241
Oh, my gosh.

05:41.240 --> 05:45.370
Hi, Beverly. I got two checks this month.
Not that I'm complaining.

05:45.440 --> 05:47.044
You're sure
they're not for two different payments?

05:47.120 --> 05:48.849
Well, I'd love to think that,

05:48.920 --> 05:52.083
but they have the same date on them
and I was paid last month.

05:52.160 --> 05:53.571
- So anyway...
- Excuse me.

05:53.640 --> 05:55.529
I'm sorry, I couldn't help but overhear.

05:55.600 --> 05:59.127
This young woman got two checks,
and I don't have any.

05:59.280 --> 06:01.123
- What's your name?
- John Harding.

06:01.280 --> 06:02.486
Well, my name is Johanna Hardin.

06:02.560 --> 06:04.324
No, I mean, my name is Maggie,

06:04.400 --> 06:07.882
but on my checks,
it's Johanna Margaret Hardin.

06:07.960 --> 06:09.450
- Right.
- So maybe there was a mix-up.

06:09.520 --> 06:12.603
Yep. And it's gonna take a minute
to figure this out.

06:12.680 --> 06:15.251
You know, it would be great
if it could be resolved soon.

06:15.880 --> 06:17.325
We'll get back to you.

06:17.640 --> 06:21.201
Damn. That woman could guard hell
if Cerberus ever needs to go to the vet.

06:21.280 --> 06:23.806
Everyone's scared of Beverly.
What do you teach?

06:23.920 --> 06:27.163
Ficto-Critical Perspectives
in Family Dynamics.

06:27.280 --> 06:31.330
Yeah, and Masks in the Modern Family,
Victorian Times to the Present Day.

06:31.520 --> 06:33.488
- Psychology department?
- Anthropology.

06:33.560 --> 06:36.803
- I don't know any anthropologists.
- No? What about you?

06:37.160 --> 06:39.401
I'm the Director of Business Development
and Outreach

06:39.480 --> 06:41.528
for the art and design students.

06:41.760 --> 06:43.285
What is that?

06:43.360 --> 06:47.081
I help graduate students strategize
for success in the art and design world.

06:47.160 --> 06:49.288
I'm sort of a bridge
between art and commerce.

06:49.360 --> 06:51.044
You seem a little young for that, no?

06:51.160 --> 06:54.084
I have an MBA
and a master's in arts management.

06:54.240 --> 06:56.527
- Nice.
- Good luck getting paid!

06:58.360 --> 07:00.442
There is something satisfying
about the feeling.

07:00.520 --> 07:02.010
Yes. That is...

07:02.080 --> 07:03.411
Felicia.

07:04.000 --> 07:06.241
What time is that Pike Fellowship meeting?

07:06.360 --> 07:09.489
- Thursday at 7:00.
- All right. Great. Thanks.

07:14.640 --> 07:16.881
It's so funny you know John Harding.

07:16.960 --> 07:18.450
We're on a committee together.

07:18.520 --> 07:21.524
He's a real panty melter. Why?

07:21.680 --> 07:25.127
Nothing. We had a mix-up with our checks

07:25.200 --> 07:27.680
- because of our names. Hardin, Harding.
- Right.

07:28.000 --> 07:31.004
He's one of the bad boys
of ficto-critical anthropology.

07:31.120 --> 07:33.282
Apparently, he was a big deal in Chicago.

07:33.360 --> 07:34.850
And now, he just does adjunct work here,

07:34.920 --> 07:37.446
but they're really salivating for him
to work full-time.

07:37.560 --> 07:39.642
- Why won't he?
- I don't know.

07:39.720 --> 07:44.044
I think it has something to do with his wife.
Apparently, she's some sort of monster.

07:44.120 --> 07:46.566
- Where did you hear this?
- Around.

07:46.640 --> 07:51.601
You know, she's got tenure at Columbia.
Georgette NÃ¸rgaard.

07:51.680 --> 07:55.480
The words "glacial" and "terrifying"
have been bandied about.

07:55.560 --> 07:58.769
Then again, I have heard myself
described as a psychotic bitch,

07:58.840 --> 08:00.922
but I think I'm actually pretty nice.

08:01.320 --> 08:03.084
So you can't believe everything you hear.

08:03.240 --> 08:04.765
If you say, "She's, like, terrified,"

08:04.880 --> 08:07.121
it's not nearly as strong as saying,
"She's terrified."

08:07.200 --> 08:09.043
"Like" is a language condom.

08:09.120 --> 08:10.121
Trust me.

08:10.560 --> 08:12.767
Where the fuck is my chicken?

08:30.360 --> 08:31.441
Hardin!

08:31.680 --> 08:32.919
Hi!

08:34.919 --> 08:36.604
What are you doing?

08:36.679 --> 08:39.808
I'm just taking a little constitutional
before my next meeting.

08:39.919 --> 08:41.763
- Did you ever get paid?
- No.

08:41.840 --> 08:42.841
You're kidding.

08:42.919 --> 08:44.729
Yeah, Beverly says the check's in the mail.

08:44.800 --> 08:46.370
- Can I join you?
- Sure.

08:47.920 --> 08:53.165
I knew this Maasai from Tanzania.
He was here to run in a marathon.

08:53.440 --> 08:56.489
He took everything about New York City
in complete stride.

08:56.560 --> 08:59.040
Nothing fazed him
until he saw a grown man following his dog

08:59.120 --> 09:00.929
and picking up his shit.

09:01.000 --> 09:03.526
He started laughing so hard, he wept.

09:03.600 --> 09:07.650
I suppose that custom could seem strange,
like, out of context.

09:10.680 --> 09:12.330
What was that?

09:12.720 --> 09:17.647
I overheard your conversation
about how "like" is a language prophylactic.

09:17.720 --> 09:18.960
Yeah.

09:19.640 --> 09:21.961
What is ficto-critical
anthropology, anyway?

09:22.080 --> 09:25.527
Well, it is a way
of writing about anthropology

09:25.600 --> 09:28.331
that blends ethnographic observation,
storytelling,

09:28.400 --> 09:30.084
and, like, theory.

09:30.160 --> 09:32.925
Do we have to walk in the circle,
or can we walk around the park?

09:33.000 --> 09:34.490
We can walk.

09:35.560 --> 09:37.483
It's so hard to find a full-time position.

09:37.680 --> 09:40.968
My wife, Georgette,
has a tenured position at Columbia,

09:41.040 --> 09:44.601
so I'm just using the time
to teach a few classes

09:44.680 --> 09:48.401
and try to write this novel that
I've had in my head for the last few years.

09:48.480 --> 09:51.086
Are you getting a lot of work done
on the novel?

09:51.160 --> 09:53.891
They say every relationship
has a gardener and a rose.

09:53.960 --> 09:55.769
Georgette is definitely the rose.

09:55.840 --> 09:58.286
- And you're the gardener.
- And I don't have a green thumb.

09:58.480 --> 10:02.644
- Maybe you're a rose in disguise.
- It'd be a very good disguise.

10:02.720 --> 10:06.611
And, I mean, she's wonderful.
It's just she's kind of destroying my life.

10:06.680 --> 10:08.842
No, I mean,
this has been a bad week, and...

10:09.000 --> 10:10.286
Content with Hermia?

10:10.400 --> 10:12.368
- It's turning into a nice day.
- Yeah.

10:12.440 --> 10:15.523
I do repent of the tedious minutes
that I with her have spent.

10:15.600 --> 10:19.241
Not Hermia, but Helena I love.

10:19.320 --> 10:22.164
Who would not change a raven for a dove?

10:23.200 --> 10:24.326
Thanks, man.

10:24.720 --> 10:27.371
We have two of those.
It's the best part of my life.

10:27.480 --> 10:29.562
- Who's the guy?
- No guy.

10:29.640 --> 10:31.449
Well, actually,
the man I've asked to be the father

10:31.520 --> 10:34.251
is named "Guy," coincidentally.

10:38.720 --> 10:41.929
- You eat like Mr. Fox!
- Who?

10:42.000 --> 10:43.729
The Roald Dahl book. The movie.

10:43.800 --> 10:45.882
- My kids love that movie.
- Yeah.

10:46.200 --> 10:49.204
I really like what you're doing, though.
Having a baby by yourself.

10:49.280 --> 10:51.806
Not that it won't be hard
because it's gonna be fucking hard.

10:51.920 --> 10:55.242
But I admire your courage.
And I love babies.

10:55.560 --> 10:57.642
I just don't like leaving my destiny...

10:57.760 --> 10:59.171
- To destiny?
- Right.

10:59.240 --> 11:03.006
But where will I go?
You can't just kick me out of our house.

11:03.080 --> 11:05.287
- I have a question for you.
- Yeah.

11:08.120 --> 11:10.521
Would you read
the first chapter of my book?

11:10.600 --> 11:12.125
- Sure.
- I know that's weird.

11:12.200 --> 11:15.841
It's just... I really want
the first reader to be like...

11:15.920 --> 11:19.367
Well, you know how you said
you're a bridge between art and commerce?

11:19.440 --> 11:20.726
Well, I need a bridge.

11:20.800 --> 11:23.644
- Perfect. Give it to me. I'll read it.
- You will? I really would appreciate it.

11:23.760 --> 11:26.240
- I don't mind at all.
- All right. Okay.

11:26.960 --> 11:29.440
Okay, great. I'll read it tonight.

11:31.400 --> 11:32.401
Perfect.

11:33.120 --> 11:34.690
I gotta go. Shoot.

11:34.760 --> 11:37.366
Shit! Shit! Shit! I gotta go. I gotta go.

11:37.520 --> 11:39.921
- I'll see you later. Thank you.
- Okay, bye!

11:44.680 --> 11:48.969
What do you make of the use of masks
in the Occupy movement?

11:49.040 --> 11:53.011
The masked revolutionary is a direct
inversion of the face of the demagogue,

11:53.120 --> 11:57.603
the essentially fascist ideal
of the magnetic individual.

11:57.800 --> 11:59.006
Sorry I'm late.

11:59.200 --> 12:03.091
John Harding,
author of many books, including

12:03.920 --> 12:08.244
Rituals of Commodity Fetishism
at the Tail End of the Empire.

12:08.360 --> 12:11.125
So, John, of course, we've been
discussing the Occupy movement...

12:11.200 --> 12:12.565
I can't help mentioning the irony

12:12.640 --> 12:15.564
that Warner Bros. owns the copyright
on the V for Vendetta mask

12:15.640 --> 12:16.926
that became the face of
the Occupy movement...

12:17.000 --> 12:18.604
Whether we like it or not,

12:18.720 --> 12:22.486
in this country, the most potent,
totemic symbols that we have

12:22.560 --> 12:24.244
are cinematic and television-based.

12:24.320 --> 12:27.369
So it only makes sense
that a radical popular movement

12:27.480 --> 12:28.641
would try to subvert them...

12:28.720 --> 12:30.529
Nevertheless, the reality of Occupy occurs

12:30.600 --> 12:34.241
within the capitalist narrative
as a kind of subplot...

12:34.320 --> 12:36.846
This sweeping cynicism of yours...

12:36.920 --> 12:41.608
If by "sweeping cynicism,"
you mean not living in a dream,

12:41.680 --> 12:42.806
then shoot me now.

12:43.120 --> 12:44.406
Maybe the way we...

12:44.520 --> 12:46.329
Nobody ever thinks
a revolution is going to happen

12:46.400 --> 12:48.243
until three days after it's happened.

12:48.320 --> 12:52.723
This is a leaderless movement.
It wasn't gonna operate on a schedule.

12:52.800 --> 12:55.451
This was a genuine populist uprising.

12:55.520 --> 12:56.806
- Yes, because...
- Absolutely.

12:56.920 --> 12:59.605
But to return to the use
of masks in politics.

12:59.680 --> 13:04.288
I am more interested in the possibility
of anonymity and group affiliation.

13:04.360 --> 13:06.089
The "I am Spartacus" maneuver,

13:06.160 --> 13:08.083
which has been
the primary tactical explanation

13:08.160 --> 13:12.563
for the use of masks among various
20th and 21st century protest movements.

13:12.720 --> 13:14.006
Including the Zapatistas,

13:14.080 --> 13:16.765
the black blocs of
the anti-globalization movement,

13:16.960 --> 13:19.566
and, of course, Pussy Riot.

13:19.880 --> 13:21.006
Thank you.

13:21.080 --> 13:23.082
Look, you don't have to help,
but will you please put that down?

13:23.200 --> 13:24.850
One moment, okay?

13:27.600 --> 13:30.604
- See? Finished.
- Great.

13:30.760 --> 13:32.603
I don't get why
you have to say the same thing

13:32.680 --> 13:35.490
in the concluding paragraph
as you do in the introduction paragraph.

13:35.560 --> 13:39.201
You're explaining your thesis,
but in a more developed form.

13:39.280 --> 13:40.964
Okay. And what's the point of that?

13:41.040 --> 13:43.930
By the time you get to your conclusion,
you've proven your thesis.

13:44.000 --> 13:45.650
So it's basically just gloating.

13:45.760 --> 13:48.001
Yeah, it is basically just gloating.

13:48.080 --> 13:50.003
They have fleas in Paul's class again.

13:50.080 --> 13:52.481
They don't have fleas, okay? They have lice.
Let me check your head.

13:52.640 --> 13:54.165
Okay, lice.

13:59.320 --> 14:00.810
You don't have lice. Okay, go.

14:00.880 --> 14:02.405
No texting at table.

14:02.520 --> 14:04.841
- I wonder where she gets that from.
- I use my phone for work.

14:04.920 --> 14:07.605
Sometimes, I want to smash it
with a hammer.

14:18.160 --> 14:19.650
Way to go, Mom.

14:19.960 --> 14:21.121
Salad?

14:25.520 --> 14:26.885
What is it?

14:26.960 --> 14:29.440
They've asked me to chair
the department at Columbia!

14:29.560 --> 14:31.927
Congratulations. That's great.

14:32.080 --> 14:34.811
- It'll be a huge time commitment.
- Still, it's a high-class problem.

14:34.920 --> 14:36.445
When will I ever get my writing done?

14:36.560 --> 14:38.085
I've promised to deliver that book
by December.

14:38.160 --> 14:39.366
Come on. You'll get a big bump in salary.

14:39.480 --> 14:42.404
- All right. What are you...
- I'm already breaking out in a rash!

14:42.480 --> 14:45.484
I've got an idea. Why don't you call
Caleb back and discuss it?

14:45.560 --> 14:47.005
- I have to.
- I know. Fine.

14:47.080 --> 14:48.684
Justine, you want to text your friend.

14:48.760 --> 14:51.240
Paul, you want to play Ninja Revinja
on your iPad? Go.

14:51.320 --> 14:55.006
I myself even have a minor text
I would like to respond to.

14:55.120 --> 14:57.885
We can stop the pretense
of having a close-knit family dinner.

14:58.000 --> 15:00.571
And we can return to the bullshit later.

15:00.720 --> 15:02.324
What? What is it?

15:03.840 --> 15:05.490
The tone, it's so unusual.

15:05.640 --> 15:09.406
- It kind of screwball-surreal. Is that right?
- Yeah, that sounds right.

15:09.480 --> 15:12.245
Screwball-surreal. That's it exactly!

15:12.320 --> 15:13.970
And the characters.

15:14.040 --> 15:18.204
Like Martin Neems, the colorless
postal worker in 1950s Connecticut

15:18.280 --> 15:21.090
and he's married
to this insane Brazilian woman,

15:21.160 --> 15:23.766
who keeps breaking out in rashes.
It's hilarious.

15:23.840 --> 15:25.490
It is, right? Really, really?

15:25.560 --> 15:29.042
And the description
of the musical collection!

15:29.120 --> 15:32.249
- Yeah, with his records, you mean?
- Yes. It's so great.

15:32.320 --> 15:33.890
- That's funny, right?
- It's great.

15:33.960 --> 15:36.440
I am so sorry. I am very, very cold.

15:36.520 --> 15:38.443
- I feel like I'm welded to the bench.
- I know.

15:38.520 --> 15:39.931
Is it okay if we go get some coffee?

15:40.040 --> 15:42.281
Actually, my apartment is
like three blocks from here.

15:42.360 --> 15:45.284
- Whatever. Yeah, yeah. Come on.
- I just need to get another sweater.

15:45.360 --> 15:47.681
I'm just... I'm deathly cold.

15:47.800 --> 15:50.485
I cannot tell you
how much I appreciate you doing this.

15:50.560 --> 15:52.369
Really, it was so much fun to read.

15:52.440 --> 15:53.487
- Really?
- Yes.

15:53.560 --> 15:55.688
Did you think the boil was weird gross
or weird funny?

16:02.840 --> 16:04.046
I sublet from a poet.

16:05.000 --> 16:06.729
Do you want some hot tea?

16:06.800 --> 16:09.610
Or, I guess that's his wine, or...

16:09.720 --> 16:13.042
But I have whiskey.
It's a little early, but...

16:14.800 --> 16:17.963
We could make a hot whiskey.
